With CMIA as a tool, Antigua and Barbuda has progressed to attain a ship register of more than 2500 vessels, which is the second largest in the world.
It means that there are a lot of Antiguan flags registered containerships and cargo vessels — more than 350 of them. Tanks, tugs and push boats have been self-regulating themselves by making an irrevocable liability and representing a substantial part of the Antigua and Barbuda register. So, the Antiguan register has gained a lot of experience in safety and efficiency at sea. This, in turn, is a sign of how strong and well established is the High Seas Fleet of Antiguans and Barbudans who sail on these vessels.
Over the years, Antiguans and Barbudans have developed a reputation for being personable and business like people and the prerequisites for good seamen. In my opinion, this reputation will continue in the future, if not grow further and allow the Antiguan and Barbudan fleet to become stronger and well respected commercially, at least as one of the nicest flags in the world.
Antigua and Barbuda is a tropical destination, situated in the heart of the Leeward Islands chain.
